node.text: I love garden tools...so much so that I probably have about 40 in my shed right now. But as a beginner, you only need about 3 - a cutting tool, digging tool, and watering tool. As you expand your garden, you may want to get into long-handled tools or specialty tools, so I've also included those in this video. At the end, a bit of a bonus on how I sharpen my tools to keep them working for years and years.

node.title: 12 Essential Gardening Tools for Beginner and Advanced Gardeners

node.text:
Honored and humbled to bring you this collaboration with @charles_dowding - we released the full version on YouTube, including Zoom conversations with each other before and after building our no-dig beds. The idea was, "How do you build a no-dig bed based on your unique climate?"

You'll see some differences in approach between myself and Charles, though I will say most of the differences are missteps in my technique - Charles has perfected his methods and in the video you'll see me note the adjustments I'll be making on future beds.

I truly hope this helps you kick off the new year feeling empowered to start growing a bit of your own food, even if you don't have much in the way of resources to buy "fancy" garden products.

Keep on growing,
Kevin

node.text:
BLASTING APHIDS 💦😱 - I've pretty much gotten to a point where I don't spray my garden at all anymore, unless I'm blasting aphids with a jet nozzle!

Aphids are the pest that myself and many other gardeners get the most questions about. Lately my go-to suggestion is to just take a hose and spray them off. They're really quite a weak insect if you can get them a few feet away from a plant.

As you can see here, they have completely colonized the flowering stalk of a mustard plant in a grow bag. If I blast them off into the mulch below, there's pretty much no chance they're coming back up so they will just live the rest of their poor sad lives figuring out what just happened to them and not eating my plants!

node.text:
POLLINATOR GARDENS - I've been incorporating WAY more flowers into the garden lately, especially these border plantings on the edges of my edible gardens. It's official...I'm a flower grower now. The dramatic increase in pollinator activity across the entire edible garden as a result is proof positive that it's having a huge positive impact on the productivity of the garden.

With my birthday coming up, I can cut myself my own flowers straight out of the garden, but if you're looking to give some flowers to a loved one for a birthday, go with @proflowers. I worked with them to hand-deliver two gorgeous bouquets (seriously, they were really pretty) to two Epic Gardening subscribers who had a birthday coming up.

You can use the code EPIC for 15% off flower delivery and a local florist will deliver an epic bouquet directly to your door or the door of a loved one. Link in bio! #ad

node.text:
💦 IRRIGATION 💦 It's absolutely absurd that it is taken this long to install drip irrigation here at the homestead, as a single day of work probably just deleted hundreds of hours of effort over the next year or so 😂.

When you're managing a pretty large garden space like we are here, the more you can systemize and automate the things that take up the most time, the better. Drip irrigation is hands down one of my favorite ways to do so.

I'll be making a full video on this for the @epichomesteading YouTube channel, and I've already made one on the main channel if you're curious how a setup like this works.

The short answer is, I used @dripdepotinc products as I've worked with them for years now. I always like to bug them with questions over email and they are more than happy to answer even the most mundane ones to get the system set up... Honestly inspirational customer service as we build out our products here at Epic Gardening!

This is a system that is adapted off of a standard garden hose, so you really can do it no matter what your garden looks like. You just run 1/2 inch mainline tubing, and then punch into it with your drip tape.

The one little fancy thing that we did in this system was having each line have a toggle valve so that you can turn the system off on a per line basis, meaning that if I have a water loving crop and a water hating crop in the same bed, I can just turn the lines off that irrigate the one that wants less water while the other one gets the drink it needs.

🐲DRAGONFRUIT MISTAKE🐉 I’ve done this more times than I want to admit, but sometimes I knock over the stems of my dragon fruit and break them off.

Fortunately, they are exceptionally easy to propagate through a variety of methods. The easiest is simply putting the stem chunk into soil.

You don’t want to bury it too deep, about an inch or so will do and any type of soil mix at the start seems to work just fine. You may have to support with a bamboo stick to keep it upright.

Alternatively, you can cut about an inch off of the bottom of the stem, let it dry, and then plant that. I’ve done that as well and it works quite effectively.

The dragon fruit here at the Homestead have been a little slower to take than the original one, so rooting these up and re-propagating into the same pots will help bush them out a bit!

POPPIN’ HERBS - Having a dedicated herb garden that’s close to the kitchen has been a game changer as I have increased my cooking. In general, many of the common herbs you’ll be growing want a pretty similar growing environment…

Full sun, loose, well draining soil that doesn’t necessarily need to be rich in organic matter.

As for varieties, here is what I am growing right now:

Shiso 
Rue
Lettuce leaf basil
Lemon thyme
Genoese basil
Greek columnar basil
African blue basil
Dill
Catmint 
Lemongrass
Tricolor sage
Italian oregano 
Lime thyme
Sweet marjoram
French lavender 
Italian parsley
Pineapple sage
Epazote

node.text:
As a gardener, you sometimes have to step back and make fun of yourself 😂. The amount of effort I've put into growing some of my more challenging crops, like loofahs is truly comical sometimes when I could just go and buy it for a few bucks.

If you just walk into any grocery store it is insane the level of variety that is available to us at our fingertips.

Obviously this mass availability is fraught with issues as far as mass scale monoculture, massive use of synthetics, soil erosion, etc but at the same time if we apply the kind of rigorous thinking that got us those kind of results at an industrial scale in our own home gardens, swapped out with less harmful practices I think we would all be absolutely floored by how much we can produce at home.

What is the crop you put the most time in love into that you could just hop over to a store and buy for a few bucks? 👀 ⬇️

node.text:
How I want to feel vs. how I actually feel about the Giant Cabbage experiment, lovingly named San Juan Cabbagestrano

😁 / 😭

This big daddy quite honestly never stood a chance based on the climate I live in, the time I planted, and the pest pressure during the season.

A great reminder that you can do most everything right but if the season is off and the conditions are off for your area, you're still not going to experience a ton of success.

Nevertheless, this was super fun and it was quite the memorial service for dear San Juan Cabbagestrano...more coming on that soon.

I sent the remains off to @jacquesinthegarden's chickens to snack on...there are so many worms in it they've got a nicely balanced meal 😂😂😂

🍅 TOMATO STORAGE 🍅 Here's a quick and simple tomato storage tip that should extend the life of your juicy, delicious tomatoes, especially the bug chinky heirlooms!

Just store it with the stem side down. That's it! The blossom end of the tomato ripens first, so storing that side down means the side that will get squishiest first is on the bottom.

On top of that, just due to the structure of the tomato, storing upside down allows for better weight distribution across the shoulders of the tomato instead of it all concentrating on one point, the bottom blossom end.

Should help them last a bit longer 👌🏽

node.text:
The garden in peak summer. I'm pretty sure I am way too harsh on myself in pretty much everything I do, but simultaneously seem unable to stop being that way.

The garden's never good enough, the business is never strong enough, the content isn't compelling enough, and so on. In many ways this obsession has led to be success of Epic Gardening, which is far beyond where I could have ever imagined. At the same time it is not the most healthy long-term mentality to hold throughout life.

Today I sat in a chair in my backyard for a while, looking at the wind rustling through the herb garden with absolutely zero thoughts in my head and realized how long it's been since I've done anything like that.

What's the point of building if you don't enjoy what you built? A constant reminder for myself, and perhaps you too if you relate.

Taking the weekend off! 

Keep on growing, Kevin

GARDEN UPDATE! It's crazy how fast a garden can grow when you set it up for success from the start and you have a diligent gardener tending to it 💯

@kehlani garden is absolutely popping off with growth in just a month since @jacquesinthegarden and I set it up 👀.

Corn is over head high, salsa garden is nearing first harvest, beans are exploding, and @kehlani is getting her first squash - and about to learn the classic summer gardener's dilemma: what the 🤬 are you supposed to do with all the squash 😂.

So awesome to see the progress...can't wait to pop up for a harvest 💯

Oops, got 25 more rare peppers bringing my total varieties to over 60 for the season. This was a COMPLETE mistake and in NO way intentional...obviously.

I can't believe I accidentally did this, now I HAVE to grow them all 🙄 and see how they taste...ughhhhh.
